---
import ArticleLayout from '../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
import TravelAffiliateBox from '../../components/TravelAffiliateBox.astro';
import { bookingSearch, googleMapsSearch, klookSearch } from '../../data/monetization';
import { existsSync, readdirSync } from 'node:fs';
import { resolve } from 'node:path';

const imageDir = resolve(process.cwd(), 'public/images/articles/japan-creation-dawn');
const imageFiles = existsSync(imageDir)
  ? readdirSync(imageDir)
      .filter((file) => /\.(jpe?g|png|webp)$/i.test(file))
      .sort((a, b) => a.localeCompare(b))
  : [];
const articleImages = imageFiles.map((file) => {
  const label = file
    .replace(/\.[^.]+$/, '')
    .replace(/^\d+[-_\s]*/, '')
    .replace(/[-_]+/g, ' ')
    .trim();

  return {
    src: `/images/articles/japan-creation-dawn/${file}`,
    alt: label ? `Article photo: ${label}` : 'Article photo',
  };
});
const photo = (index: number) => articleImages[index];

const toc = [
  { id: 'before-samurai', label: 'Before the samurai story' },
  { id: 'rice', label: 'Rice changed society' },
  { id: 'himiko', label: 'Himiko and Yamatai' },
  { id: 'kofun', label: 'Kofun and Yamato' },
  { id: 'buddhism', label: 'Buddhism and statecraft' },
  { id: 'taika', label: 'Taika and ritsuryo' },
  { id: 'nara-heian', label: 'Nara to Heian' },
  { id: 'warriors', label: 'The road to warriors' },
];

const related = [
  {
    title: 'Origins to Heian',
    description:
      'The category page for early Japanese history before the warrior age dominates the story.',
    href: '/ancient-heian/',
    kicker: 'Origins',
  },
  {
    title: 'Sengoku',
    description:
      'After the foundations are in place, follow the later age of warlords, castles, and unification.',
    href: '/sengoku/',
    kicker: 'Warrior age',
  },
  {
    title: 'Hidden Spots',
    description:
      'Historical places for travelers who want more than the standard first-time Japan route.',
    href: '/hidden-japan/',
    kicker: 'Travel',
  },
];

const asukaTravelDestinations = [
  {
    name: 'Asuka',
    description:
      'A compact landscape of early court politics, burial mounds, Buddhist beginnings, and the pre-Nara state.',
    placeHref: googleMapsSearch('Asuka Nara Japan history'),
    stayHref: bookingSearch('Asuka, Nara, Japan'),
  },
  {
    name: 'Horyu-ji and Ikaruga',
    description:
      'A clear place to connect Buddhism, early architecture, Prince Shotoku memory, and the Asuka-Nara transition.',
    placeHref: googleMapsSearch('Horyu-ji Ikaruga Nara Japan'),
    stayHref: bookingSearch('Ikaruga, Nara, Japan'),
  },
];

const capitalTravelDestinations = [
  {
    name: 'Nara',
    description:
      'The best practical base for early Buddhism, ancient capitals, Todai-ji, and the political world before Kyoto.',
    placeHref: googleMapsSearch('Nara Japan ancient history'),
    stayHref: bookingSearch('Nara, Japan'),
    activityHref: klookSearch('Nara Japan history tour'),
  },
  {
    name: 'Kyoto',
    description:
      'The natural entry point for Heian court culture, later aristocratic memory, temples, literature, and imperial ritual.',
    placeHref: googleMapsSearch('Kyoto Heian history'),
    stayHref: bookingSearch('Kyoto, Japan'),
    activityHref: klookSearch('Kyoto history tour'),
  },
];
---

<ArticleLayout
  title="The Dawn of Japan: How a Country Took Shape Before the Samurai"
  description="A clear guide to early Japanese history for readers who know samurai and castles, but not how Japan first became a state."
  subtitle="Before castles, warlords, and the samurai image, Japan was shaped by rice, ritual, tombs, Buddhism, law, capitals, and the slow rise of warrior power."
  kicker="Origins to Heian"
  datePublished="2026-05-08"
  readingTime="11 min read"
  category="Early Japanese history"
  toc={toc}
  related={related}
>
  <h2 id="before-samurai">Before the samurai story</h2>

  <p>
    For many international readers, Japanese history begins with samurai,
    castles, ninja, or the old streets of Kyoto. Films, games, and historical
    dramas often enter Japan through the age of warriors.
  </p>

  <p>
    But the story of Japan begins much earlier.
  </p>

  <p>
    Japan was not always the single country people imagine today. The idea of a
    Japan stretching naturally from Hokkaido to Okinawa belongs to a much later
    historical world. In ancient times, the archipelago was home to many
    communities, regional powers, ritual centers, and competing elites. Over
    centuries, they absorbed ideas from the Asian continent, fought over land
    and authority, built capitals, wrote origin stories, and slowly assembled a
    larger political order.
  </p>

  <div class="article-callout">
    <p>
      <strong>Reader's map:</strong> This article follows Japan before the
      samurai became the main historical image: from rice farming and Queen
      Himiko to burial mounds, Buddhism, law, Nara, Heian Kyoto, and the first
      signs of warrior power.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Ancient Japan was not a quiet preface. It was the first great transformation:
    the long process by which Japan began to become Japan.
  </p>

  {photo(0) && (
    <figure class="article-photo">
      <img src={photo(0)?.src} alt={photo(0)?.alt} loading="lazy" />
    </figure>
  )}

  <h2 id="rice">Rice changed society</h2>

  <p>
    The first major turning point was the shift from Jomon to Yayoi. Jomon
    communities lived through hunting, gathering, fishing, and the use of
    pottery. They formed settlements and developed a rich material culture.
    It is too simple to call Jomon society a peaceful paradise, but it was not
    yet a rice-based political world built around stored harvests, irrigation,
    and organized hierarchy.
  </p>

  <p>
    Yayoi society changed that. Wet-rice agriculture spread, and rice required
    land, water, timing, and cooperation. A field had to be managed. Water had
    to be shared or controlled. Harvests could be stored. Once something can be
    stored, differences appear: rich land and poor land, those who hold surplus
    and those who do not, those who protect stores and those who try to take
    them.
  </p>

  <p>
    A change in food changed settlement. A change in settlement changed power.
    The path from village to state begins here.
  </p>

  {photo(1) && (
    <figure class="article-photo">
      <img src={photo(1)?.src} alt={photo(1)?.alt} loading="lazy" />
    </figure>
  )}

  <h2 id="himiko">Himiko and Yamatai: the first great mystery</h2>

  <p>
    In the third century, China was divided among Wei, Wu, and Shu, the world
    later remembered through the <em>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</em>. In
    Chinese records from that world, a queen appears in the Japanese
    archipelago: Himiko.
  </p>

  <p>
    In 239, Himiko is said to have sent envoys to Wei and received the title
    “Queen of Wa friendly to Wei.” The important point is not only her name.
    It is that early Japan is first seen through outside records. The
    archipelago itself did not yet leave the kind of written historical record
    that later states would produce.
  </p>

  <p>
    Himiko is described as a ruler with religious or shamanic authority. In this
    early world, politics and ritual were not cleanly separated. To govern was
    also to read signs, perform rites, and stand between people and the unseen.
  </p>

  <p>
    The major problem is Yamatai, the polity Himiko ruled. Was it in Kyushu, in
    western Japan closer to the continent? Or was it in the Kinai region, near
    the later center of Yamato power? This is not just a map puzzle. The location
    of Yamatai changes how we imagine the birth of political centrality in Japan.
  </p>

  <p>
    At the entrance to Japanese history, there is not a neat answer. There is a
    fog. That is part of what makes ancient Japan worth reading.
  </p>

  {photo(2) && (
    <figure class="article-photo">
      <img src={photo(2)?.src} alt={photo(2)?.alt} loading="lazy" />
    </figure>
  )}

  <h2 id="kofun">Kofun and Yamato: power written in tombs</h2>

  <p>
    After Yamatai, the written record becomes harder to follow. But something
    else becomes visible: huge burial mounds.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Kofun period is named for these tombs. The most famous form is the
    keyhole-shaped mound, or <em>zenpo-koen-fun</em>. To build one required labor,
    planning, tools, and authority. A tomb of that scale is not only a grave. It
    is a statement that someone had the power to mobilize a community.
  </p>

  <p>
    As similar tomb forms spread, they suggest that regional elites were being
    drawn into a shared political culture. This is where the outline of the
    Yamato polity becomes clearer.
  </p>

  <p>
    But Yamato should not be imagined too quickly as a modern-style state. It
    was not born as a fully centralized government ruling the entire archipelago
    from day one. It is better to begin with a coalition of powerful elites:
    local leaders bound together by rank, ritual, marriage, force, and exchange.
  </p>

  <p>
    Japan's beginning was not a single straight line. It was a gradual process
    in which many powers were pulled into a larger order.
  </p>

  {photo(3) && (
    <figure class="article-photo">
      <img src={photo(3)?.src} alt={photo(3)?.alt} loading="lazy" />
    </figure>
  )}

  <h2 id="buddhism">Buddhism was religion, culture, and statecraft</h2>

  <p>
    In the mid-sixth century, Buddhism was transmitted to Japan from Baekje, one
    of the Korean kingdoms. Traditional accounts give 538 or 552 as the date of
    its official introduction.
  </p>

  <p>
    To modern readers, Buddhism may sound like a question of temples and belief.
    For ancient rulers, it was much more. Buddhist images, scriptures, temple
    architecture, scholarship, calendars, writing, and court culture arrived as
    part of a wider continental package.
  </p>

  <p>
    Accepting Buddhism was not simply a matter of liking a new religion. It was
    tied to the question of whether Japan would adopt a more continental style
    of state formation.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why the conflict between the Soga and Mononobe clans matters. The
    Soga supported Buddhism. The Mononobe are remembered as defenders of older
    ritual practices tied to native deities and clan authority. In 587, Soga no
    Umako defeated Mononobe no Moriya, and the Buddhist side won.
  </p>

  <p>
    The age of Empress Suiko, Prince Umayado, later remembered as Prince
    Shotoku, and Soga no Umako became a moment when Japan faced the continent
    directly. Envoys were sent to Sui China. Institutions, rank, writing, and
    Buddhist culture became tools for imagining a more organized state.
  </p>

  <p>
    This does not mean every later legend about Shotoku should be read literally.
    Ancient history often tells us two stories at once: what may have happened,
    and what later generations needed to remember.
  </p>

  {photo(4) && (
    <figure class="article-photo">
      <img src={photo(4)?.src} alt={photo(4)?.alt} loading="lazy" />
    </figure>
  )}

  <TravelAffiliateBox
    destinations={asukaTravelDestinations}
    title="Visit the places behind early Buddhism"
    intro="Asuka and Horyu-ji fit this part of the story: early court politics, Buddhist transmission, burial mounds, and the world before Nara became the capital."
  />

  <h2 id="taika">Taika and ritsuryo: trying to become a state</h2>

  <p>
    In 645, Prince Naka no Oe and Nakatomi no Kamatari overthrew Soga no Iruka.
    The event is known as the Isshi Incident, and it opened the way to what is
    traditionally called the Taika Reform.
  </p>

  <p>
    This was not just palace drama. It was an attempt to pull power away from
    dominant clan elites and move toward a more emperor-centered state.
  </p>

  <p>
    The era name “Taika” matters. To create an era name is to claim authority
    over time itself. In East Asia, calendars and era names were political. They
    showed who defined the order of the world. By setting its own era name, the
    Japanese court was making a statement: this polity would define its own
    time.
  </p>

  <p>
    The reform ideal was known as public land and public people. Land and
    population were to be grasped by the state, rather than left entirely under
    private clan control. Later ritsuryo law, inspired by Chinese models, aimed
    to organize offices, ranks, provinces, registers, taxes, and military
    obligations.
  </p>

  <p>
    But state formation did not move in a straight line. In 672, the Jinshin War
    broke out over succession after Emperor Tenji. The victor, Emperor Tenmu,
    strengthened the court and is often associated with the shaping of the names
    “Japan” and “emperor.” The compilation of the <em>Kojiki</em> and
    <em>Nihon Shoki</em> also belongs to this broader project of state memory.
  </p>

  <p>
    A new state needs laws. It also needs a story about where it came from.
  </p>

  <h2 id="nara-heian">From Nara to Heian: the light and shadow of Buddhist rule</h2>

  <p>
    In 710, the capital moved to Heijo-kyo, today associated with Nara. This was
    the age in which the ritsuryo state took visible form: offices, provinces,
    registers, taxes, and great Buddhist institutions.
  </p>

  <p>
    Emperor Shomu tried to protect the realm through Buddhism. In 752, the Great
    Buddha of Todai-ji was consecrated. The statue was not only a religious
    object. It was also a political symbol: a massive attempt to answer crisis
    through Buddhist power.
  </p>

  <p>
    Yet Buddhism's closeness to government created a problem. If Buddhist
    institutions could protect the state, could Buddhist figures also dominate
    the state? The monk Dokyo, favored by Empress Shotoku in the eighth century,
    became the clearest warning sign. His rise suggested that religious
    authority might move dangerously close to imperial authority.
  </p>

  <p>
    In 794, Emperor Kanmu moved the capital to Heian-kyo, the city later known
    as Kyoto. This was not just a change of address. It was an attempt to step
    away from the political weight of Nara Buddhism and renew court rule in a
    new capital.
  </p>

  <p>
    The Heian period also reminds us that “Japan” was still being made at its
    edges. In the northeast, there were peoples not fully under court control.
    The campaigns involving Sakanoue no Tamuramaro and the Emishi leader Aterui
    show that the ancient court's authority was expanding, contested, and
    incomplete.
  </p>

  {photo(5) && (
    <figure class="article-photo">
      <img src={photo(5)?.src} alt={photo(5)?.alt} loading="lazy" />
    </figure>
  )}

  <TravelAffiliateBox
    destinations={capitalTravelDestinations}
    title="Follow the capital route from Nara to Kyoto"
    intro="Nara and Kyoto are the most practical bases for seeing how Buddhist statecraft, court culture, and Heian memory still shape travel routes today."
  />

  <h2 id="warriors">The elegance of Heian, and the road to warriors</h2>

  <p>
    Heian Japan is famous for courtly elegance: poetry, rank, ceremony, Fujiwara
    no Michinaga, Murasaki Shikibu, and <em>The Tale of Genji</em>. That image is
    real, but it is not the whole story.
  </p>

  <p>
    Under the surface, the land system was changing. The ideal of public land
    weakened. Private estates, known as <em>shoen</em>, expanded. Aristocrats and
    temples held land in the provinces, and land needed protection. Armed men
    who guarded estates gradually gained importance. These men were part of the
    world from which samurai power emerged.
  </p>

  <p>
    In 939, Taira no Masakado rebelled in the Kanto region and called himself a
    “new emperor.” The rebellion failed, but it revealed something important:
    far from Kyoto, armed regional power could imagine a political order of its
    own.
  </p>

  <p>
    Fujiwara power reached a peak in the eleventh century, but it too changed.
    From 1086, retired emperors such as Shirakawa ruled through insei, or
    cloistered government. Around them stood armed guards such as the Hokumen no
    Bushi, the northern-face warriors.
  </p>

  <p>
    By the twelfth century, warrior families were no longer background figures.
    The Hogen and Heiji disturbances opened the way for Taira no Kiyomori, who
    became Grand Minister of State in 1167. Politics was no longer only the world
    of court nobles.
  </p>

  <p>
    The age of warriors did not appear from nowhere. It grew out of the Heian
    world: land disputes, estate protection, regional military power, court
    politics, and the weakening of older systems.
  </p>

  {photo(6) && (
    <figure class="article-photo">
      <img src={photo(6)?.src} alt={photo(6)?.alt} loading="lazy" />
    </figure>
  )}

  <h2 id="japan-took-shape">Japan took shape by changing again and again</h2>

  <p>
    The story from Jomon to Heian is not a preface to the “real” history of
    samurai and castles. It is the foundation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Hunting and gathering gave way to rice agriculture. Small communities became
    regional powers. Yamatai gave way to the mystery of Yamato. Burial mounds
    made power visible. Buddhism brought continental statecraft. Ritsuryo law
    tried to organize land and people. Nara built a Buddhist state. Heian Kyoto
    refined court culture while warriors grew beneath the surface.
  </p>

  <p>
    Japan was not born as a finished country. It took shape by absorbing outside
    ideas, resisting them, moving capitals, writing myths, building laws,
    fighting over land, and expanding the reach of the court.
  </p>

  <p>
    The samurai age is fascinating. But the deepest entrance to Japanese history
    lies earlier, before the sword becomes the main symbol. It begins with the
    long, difficult dawn of Japan itself.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>

